Humans have distinct patterning to their life history traits, perhaps most notably we require adult provisioning for a long period of time, which constitutes childhood \citep{Bock2002ChildhoodCourse, Bogin1997EvolutionaryChildhood, Leigh2002EvolutionGrowth}. The emergence of this phase in our lineage has been connected to other specifically human traits, including early weaning, short inter birth intervals, cooperative breeding and the presence of multiple dependent offspring in a family \citep{Bogin1997EvolutionaryChildhood, Kaplan1996ASocieties, Kramer2005ChildrensHumans, Kramer2010CooperativeHumans, Kramer2011TheHelp, Kramer2010PooledTrade-offs}. It is believed that this period is important for acquiring skills and knowledge, which are necessary to exploit our species' complex niche \citep{Kaplan2000ALongevity, Kaplan2015FertilityEvolution, Robson2003TheEconomics, Schuppli2012HowHumans}. The connection between life history, knowledge and the prevalence in our niche of nutrient-dense, difficult-to-acquire food resources has been extensively explored in \cite{Kaplan2000ALongevity}. Individuals who postponed reproduction in order to improve their understanding of the environment and increase their ability to extract its resources were hence selected thanks to the benefits reaped in adulthood, when overproduction could support dependent offspring \citep{Hill1999}. \cite{Schuppli2016LifeNiches} present a comparative analysis supporting this hypothesis, as they show that niche complexity correlates with adult provisioning and lengthy development in carnivora and primates respectively. But testing this hypothesis in our species is difficult. Previous research focused on describing age specific patterns of foraging efficiency \citep{Bird2002ConstraintsGrowing, Bird2005MarduHistories, Bird2002ChildrenForaging, BlurtonJones2002SelectionGather, Bock2002LearningBotswana, Crittenden2013JuvenileHistory, Gurven2006HowSpan, Koster2020TheVariation}, or knowledge \citep{Koster2016WisdomElders, Schniter2021Age-AppropriateChoyeros}. But the level of modelling detail reserved to somatic and cerebral growth \citep{Kuzawa2014MetabolicDevelopment, Gonzalez-Forero2017AEvolution} has not extended to knowledge acquisition. 

With respect to somatic and cerebral growth we know, for example, that a ten years old child's brain has already reached its adult size, before the reproductive tissues start to develop and long before somatic growth is completed (see dashed lines in figure \ref{fig:3curves}, adapted from \cite{Bogin1997EvolutionaryChildhood}) . We also know that children's bodies develop at a slower rate between the faster growth periods of infancy and adolescence. On the contrary, we don't know with enough precision, how knowledge increases map onto these changes. Does knowledge increase track cerebral growth (e.g. green curve in figure \ref{fig:3curves}), as it would be expected if the only condition necessary for the acquisition of knowledge was brain development? Or is knowledge simply a prerequisite to reproduce and it can be acquired in a short time, so that it increases just before individuals reach sexual maturity (purple curve, figure \ref{fig:3curves})? Previous studies report a slow, long period of knowledge acquisition, inconsistent with the aforementioned explanations, but as yet we do not have a clear understanding of how learning is patterned. Ascertaining the shape of knowledge acquisition can give insights on its role for the evolution of childhood.


