In this paper, we focus on the acquisition of ecological knowledge because of its likely association with fitness, for example through increased returns when foraging \citep{Koster2016WisdomElders, Reyes-Garcia2016TheSocieties}, or health benefits in possessors of ecological knowledge \citep{Reyes-Garcia2008Non-marketSociety} and their families \citep{McDade2007EthnobotanicalAmazon}. Furthermore, we make three specific contributions to our understanding of how knowledge is acquired. 

First, we develop a novel analysis of knowledge using the principles of Item Response Theory \citep{Osteen2010AnStructures}. We model knowledge as a latent variable measured with several independent survey tools. This method also allows for the emergence of different dimensions of knowledge from the data, which allow to identify gender-specific patterns of learning. 

Second, we describe in detail the variation in knowledge dependent on age and sex. Concerning age, we focus on a sample ranging from 5-26 years and we analyze its effects as an ordered categorical variable, allowing the relational structure to emerge from the data rather than be arbitrarily imposed. This is in contrast to previous studies, which over-impose linear or logistic regressions and focus on adults (\cite{Bortolotto2015KnowledgeBrazil} 21-86 years, \cite{Geng2016TraditionalProvince} 21-91 years, \cite{Koster2016WisdomElders} 10-80 years, with few individuals < 15; \cite{Schniter2021Age-AppropriateChoyeros} 5 to 86 years, only 7 individuals < 30), or divide children in large age categories (\cite{Cruz-garcia2018ChildrensInterface} children 7-14 divided in two categories; \cite{Quinlan2016ChildrensVillage} kids from 4 to 17 years divided in three categories; \cite{Gallois2017LocalCulture} divides only between children and adults). This allows us to explore the relation between age and knowledge in the most important phases of our development with more precision, in an attempt to understand how knowledge acquisition maps onto other life history traits. 
Following the assumption that labor division along gender lines entails knowledge specializations, we also investigate sex differences in ecological knowledge. Our main novel contribution are insights provided by the dimension analysis. Previous studies provide contrasting results on whether boys and girls differ in their levels of ecological knowledge \citep{Blacutt-Rivero2016LocalBolivia, Gallois2017LocalCulture, Schniter2021Age-AppropriateChoyeros, Setalaphruk2007ChildrensThailand, Cruz-garcia2018ChildrensInterface, Geng2016TraditionalProvince}. Here, we propose the existence of gender specific areas of knowledge which need to be taken into consideration when focusing on gender differences in knowledge.

