Third, we supplement our descriptive approach to variation in the patterns of how knowledge is acquired with a causal analysis of the factors influencing this variation. We focus on three specific factors: first, exposure and practice (gendered-activities effects); second, access to adult experts or peers (household and family composition effects), and third opportunities for learning (formal education effects). These were chosen because they were expected to represent opportunities for learning through practice or exposure to models of behavior in the particular ethnographic context. 
%In particular, according to the hypothesis that childhood evolved as a period to acquire knowledge and skills, participation to foraging or other activities is key to knowledge acquisition \citep{Kaplan2000ALongevity}. Moreover, gender differences are thought to arise through division of tasks, rather than because of innate differences between the sexes. 
Our specific contribution in the context of exposure and practice is to show how gendered differences in knowledge are related to the differential engagement in sex specific activities in different subsets of the ecological niche, consistent with expectations that such differences are not necessarily innate. %the first of its kind,
Household composition is leveraged to identify how adult experts or peers \citep{Page2021ChildrenAgta, Ruddle1993TheKnowledge, Ohmagari1997TransmissionCanada, Boyette2013SocialRepublic, Lew-Levy2017HowSkills}, in addition to parents \citep{Lozada2006CulturalArgentina, Hewlett1986CulturalPygmies}, might influence the acquisition of knowledge about the local environment. Similarly, we examine the effects on knowledge acquisition of birth order \citep{Quinlan2016ChildrensVillage}, to determine whether late-borns gain more access to older sibling role models, and/or early-borns enjoy preferential access to parental and grandparental wisdom. Finally, participation in formal education can lower exposure to locally relevant ecological knowledge, as time invested in school attendance could reduce opportunities for acquiring information about the environment \citep{Reyes-Garcia2010SchoolingOther, Quinlan2016ChildrensVillage}.


