The data used for this study were collected in a village close to the forest of Ngezi, on Pemba, the northern island of the Zanzibar archipelago, a semi-autonomous zone of Tanzania (see figure \ref{fig:inset}). 
%history/islam
Pemba is part of the Swahili world, with multiple historical and cultural influences: first the Bantu expansion from the mainland, then 700 years of trade in the Indian ocean, and later Portuguese, Omani and British colonial power \citep{Fleisher2015WhenMaritime, LaViolette2009TheAD}. Especially important has been the influence of the Arab world and Islam, since at least the eleventh century and then during the rule of the Omani Sultanate, which was weakened by the British at the end of the 19th century, but formally deposed only in 1963/4 \citep{Fleisher2013The600-950}.

%location
The island, located just below the equator (5Â°S), enjoys a tropical climate and mild seasonality, with an alternation between drier and rainier seasons following the monsoon cycle. Its densely distributed population ($428/km^2$, about twice as high as Switzerland) mostly lives in rural areas (around 80\%, according to the \cite{NationalBureauofStatisticsMinistryofFinance2014BasicReport}) and depends largely on agriculture, fishing and other land based activities \citep{Andrews2021ForestInstitutions.}. 

%reliance on natural resources 
The forest of Ngezi is the largest remaining patch of rain forest in Pemba, and the people living around it depend on terrestrial and maritime habitats for more than 80\% of their livelihoods. Most of the income of the typical household in the area around Ngezi comes either from fishing (9.7\%), agriculture (farming 20.6\%, livestock 3.9\%, agroforestry 4.2\%, 11.9\% clove production, which is the main cash crop on the island) or the forest itself (forest products, mainly firewood, for 33\% of total income for the average family in the area around Ngezi forest \citep{Andrews2021ForestInstitutions.}). Hunting is relatively rare among the adult population, in large part because of the scarce wildlife of reasonable size, but still present in many areas of the island \citep{Walsh2007IslandOcean}. %

%children role 
Children comprise a large part of the growing population of Pemba, where 48\% of inhabitants are below 15 years of age \citep{NationalBureauofStatisticsMinistryofFinance2014BasicReport}. Young people divide their time between domestic and farming chores, education at both the state and Koranic schools and play. There is variability in the extent to which children and teenagers interact with the natural environment, mainly when they forage, depending on personal inclination and their familial or environmental conditions. Kids gather shellfish and other invertebrates on the shores fringing the mangrove forest, or hunt birds in the forest. 

\subsection{Data collection}
\emph{Village census:} With government approval for research, IP visited all households in the village between June and August 2019. The objective of this survey was to record a full village census with relevant household level characteristics, so that background variables on subjects (opportunistically sampled, see below) were known. The survey also provided the opportunity to introduce the project to the full community, and to obtain approval for future interviews with the children. 

\emph{Knowledge interviews:} Using an opportunistic sampling procedure - effectively children and young adults volunteering for interview - IP conducted a survey instrument measuring knowledge of the natural environment (as defined in SI\ref{SI:knowledge}); the extent and impact of any sampling bias that could have arisen from this procedure is examined in SI\ref{SI:Sampling bias}. In sum, 93 individuals between 5 and 26 years of age participated in the knowledge interviews. These consisted of three different types of questions, namely: (i) freelisting questions in which children were asked to name all the living creatures (\emph{viumbe}, which include plants, different kinds of animals and also spirits that are thought to inhabit nature) found in the village/cultivated fields, in the forest or in the sea. The named items were then checked for misspelling, and then again with local and international collaborators to ensure appropriate identification of the answered items; (ii) a list of 50 multiple choice quiz questions probing different aspects of ecological knowledge, each with two options, developed with the help of both the Department of Forestry and Non Renewable Natural Resources (DFNRNR) and focus groups with adults in the village; (iii) a task of image recognition using pictures collected around the village or elsewhere in Pemba, in which children were asked to name all the living beings appearing in a sequence of 27 photographs. Answers given to each picture were rated as acceptable or non-acceptable during a focus group with adults in the village following data collection. More details on the interviews and data can be found in SI \ref{SI:data_details}.

\subsection{Causal framework}
Data collection and analysis were informed by preliminary work aimed at describing the causal and non-causal effects of factors influencing knowledge. Specifically, we described all the aspects of individuals that are expected to influence Knowledge in a Direct Acyclic Graph (DAG) (see figure \ref{fig:DAG} and SI \ref{SI:DAG}). A DAG is a heuristic generative model that allows derivation of a causal estimand for one variable on a dependent one \citep{Pearl1995CausalResearch}. Each causal query may require a different statistical procedure that includes different variables. 
In our DAG, for example, Sex does not have a direct effect on Knowledge (no direct arrow Sex $\rightarrow$ Knowledge), but rather its effect is mediated by Activities. If we want to estimate the total effect of Sex on Knowledge, we cannot include Activities in the analysis. The causal effect of Sex on Knowledge, on the contrary, is estimated once all other factors mediating its effect (Activities, Schooling) are included in the analysis. 

