We relied on the DAG described above to plan data collection, so that all the variables would be recorded, as well as to define the analyses described below. The analysis can be divided in a descriptive and a causal section. The first illustrates how knowledge changes with age; the causal section, instead, describes the effect of sex, activities, family and schooling on the development of knowledge. 

\subsection{Analysis} \label{m:m&m}

We developed multiple Bayesian models targeting our different inference goals, each composed of two different parts. The core of the models is an Item Response Theory (IRT) model. IRT models, initially developed as a mean to grade tests in pedagogy \citep{Osteen2010AnStructures}, aim at estimating one or multiple latent traits, such as individual knowledge ($K_i$), from answers to questions while simultaneously allowing questions to vary in difficulty ($b_j$) and discrimination ($a_j$, i.e. how helpful they are at discriminating between high and low knowledge individuals).
So for each question $j$, an individual $i$ has a probability $p$ of answering correctly $Y_{i,j}$ (see equation \ref{Y1} and \ref{Y2}); that is, naming a specific item in the freelist, answering correctly an item in the quiz, or recognizing an item in the image recognition task. The quiz questions differ from the other two types because the correct answer can be given simply by guessing, and thus required a 3PL IRT model, which includes a pseudo-guessing parameter $c_j$ \citep{Osteen2010AnStructures}. All three types of data contribute to the estimation of one single measure of knowledge for each individual (see SI \ref{SI:model_details} for an extended description of the model's functioning and implications). 

\begin{align}
Y_{i,j} &\sim \text{Bernoulli}(p_{i,j}) \label{Y1}\\
\text{logit}(p_{i,j}) &= a_j (K_i - b_j) \label{Y2}
\end{align}

The knowledge estimated by the IRT part of the model is then used as a dependent variable in the second part of the model, which estimates the effect of various factors on individual knowledge. Age is included in all models as an ordered categorical variable, so that there is a sex specific maximum effect for age $\beta_s$ and each year adds one proportion $\delta_y$ of the total effect 
This means that the curve of the relation between knowledge and age emerges from the data themselves, rather than being imposed to be a specific function in the model design. Model 1, described by equation \ref{M1}, includes varying random effects $\alpha_i$ for individuals in addition to this sex and age specific estimate, and can hence tell us the total effect of age and sex combined. 

\begin{align} 
 K_i &= \omega + \alpha_i \sigma_{\alpha} + \beta_s \sum_{y=1}^{Age_i}  \delta_y \label{M1}  
\end{align}

The full version of this model is a compensatory Multidimensional IRT model \citep{Reckase2009MultidimensionalTheory}, that allows different dimensions of knowledge to emerge from the data. This is aimed at determining whether the individuals in our sample are experts in certain aspects of the environment, while having lower knowledge in others; in other words if there is knowledge specialization. The probability individual $i$ has of answering a single question $j$ correctly is the sum of multiple probabilities for each dimension $d$, and individuals are assigned a measure of knowledge in each dimension $K_{i,d}$. This approach allows us to partition the variation among knowledge of individuals in any number of dimensions, see equations S\ref{Y3} and S\ref{Y4} ans SI \ref{SI:dimensions}.

%in supplementary now
%\begin{align*}
%Y_{i,j} &\sim \text{Bernoulli}(logit (p_{i,j})) \label{Y3}\\
%p_{i,j} &= \sum_{d=1}^{d=D} p_{i,j,d} \label{Y4}
%\end{align*}

The results of this first model are mainly descriptive. 
The models described below aim instead at estimating the causal effect of the other factors included in the DAG in figure \ref{fig:DAG}. In order, model 2 (equation \ref{M2}) includes also household level varying random effects $\eta_h$ and effects of each of the ten possible activities $\gamma_{act}$ on individual knowledge (see SI \ref{SI:activities} for a description of these activities).
Model 3 (equation \ref{M3}) estimates the effect of co-residing with either parent for individuals of both sexes ($\psi_s$ is the sex specific effect of being in the same household with mothers, $\phi_s$ with fathers). 
Further models to test the effect of other factors such as schooling and birth order are described in SI \ref{SI:model_details}. 

\begin{align} 
K_i &= \omega + \alpha_i \sigma_{\alpha} + \eta_h \sigma_{\eta} + \beta_s \sum_{y=1}^{Age_i} \delta_y + \sum_{act=1}^{10} \gamma_{act}  \text{Activity}_{i,act}  \label{M2}\\
K_i &= \omega + \alpha_i \sigma_{\alpha} + \eta_h \sigma_{\eta} + \beta_s \sum_{y=1}^{Age_i} \delta_y + \psi_s \text{Mother}_i + \phi_s \text{Father}_i \label{M3}
\end{align}

The priors used for the model are:
\begin{align*} 
a_j &\sim \text{Half-Normal}(0,1)\\
b_j &\sim \text{Normal}(0,2)\\
\omega &\sim \text{Normal}(-5,3)\\
\beta_s &\sim \text{Folded-Normal}(3,1,0)\\
\delta_y &\sim \text{Dirichlet}(0.5)\\
\sigma_{\alpha}, \sigma_{\eta} &\sim \text{Exponential}(1)\\
\alpha_i, \eta_h, \gamma_{act}, \phi_s, \psi_s &\sim \text{Normal}(0,1)\\
\end{align*}

The priors for the question parameters $a_j$ and $b_j$ are weakly informative. The prior for $a$, a normal distribution limited to positive values, ensures that more knowledgeable individuals have higher values than less knowledgeable ones - instead of a reverted axis. The slightly less constrained prior for $b$ allows the axis of the latent knowledge to expand to accommodate all the values for each question (to see what happens when changing the priors for $b$, see figure S\ref{fig:IRT_diffpriors}). Note that the individual knowledge measures $K_i$ do not require a prior distribution, but is informed by the combination of the priors for $a$ and $b$.
For the parameters $\alpha_i$, $\eta_h$, $\sigma_{\alpha}$, $\sigma_{\eta}$, $\delta_y$,  $\gamma_{act}$, $\psi_s$, and  $\phi_s$ weakly informative regularizing priors have been used. The priors for the parameters $\omega$ and $\beta_s$, instead, have been chosen to allow the function to expand in the negative space where the values of knowledge are placed by the IRT model.



The models were fitted using the Hamiltonian Monte Carlo engine Stan \citep{StanDevelopmentTeam2021StanManual} from CmdStan 0.4.0.9 \citep{StanDevelopmentTeam2021CmdStanR:CmdStan.} in R 4.1.0 \citep{Team2021R:Computin}, with the help of the Statistical Rethinking R package, version 2.13 \citep{McElreath2020StatisticalRethinking}. 
All models were run on multiple threads to reduce the fitting times. 
For all analyses, visual inspection of traceplots, Gelman-Rubin diagnostic and effective number of samples seem to indicate good model convergence.

Parameters estimation in the Bayesian framework does not return point estimates, but rather a posterior distribution of possible values for a parameter. The figures in the result section reflect this feature, e.g. each line in figure \ref{fig:age_sex} is draw by a set of values sampled from the posterior distribution of parameters.
Finally, prior to fitting to real data, all models have been tested with simulated data, as described in SI \ref{SI:Simulation}. This allowed to ensure that the models could recover "real" parameter values.
Simulation as well as all the other code necessary to reproduce these analyses is available on GitHub (https://github.com/lalla-ilaria/Children\_eco\_knowledge)

\subsection{Results}

\emph{Descriptive results:} 
where we measure the association of age and sex with knowledge, as estimated with model 1 (equation \ref{M1}).
In agreement with previous studies, knowledge in our model increases along all sampled ages. The lines in figure \ref{fig:age_sex} show the estimated increase in knowledge per each year of age, plotted over the dots representing individual measures of knowledge resulting from the IRT part of the model.
We can see that knowledge increases with varying rate: it grows quite steeply during early and middle childhood, it keeps increasing during most of adolescence and then it appears to start leveling off around 20 years of age, although we do not have many data points for our oldest ages. Age-specific effects, shown in figure S\ref{fig:year_effect}, are largest for ages 7 and 11, suggesting that the time around these years has higher importance for knowledge than, for example, ages 20-25 (see SI\ref{SI:age_note} for reasons why we are confident in our age estimations). 

Sex differences in ecological knowledge, as identified from the one dimensional model, are clearly visible in Figure 4. This difference appears during the juvenile period, between 7 and 12 years, right when division of labor begins to emerge, and results in higher undifferentiated ecological knowledge among the oldest boys in our sample when compared to the oldest girls. But this one dimensional description of knowledge does not tell the whole story. Indeed, when  we allow the model to partition knowledge into more than one dimension (see section \ref{m:m&m} in Methods), we find patterns which reveal more about gender specialization on Pemba (figure \ref{fig:dimensions}). Three main patterns emerge: one in which both sexes acquire knowledge at similar rate, plausibly representing general knowledge; one where there is a sharp increase in knowledge only among boys, and no age effect among girls, which probably reflects a male-specific dimension of knowledge; and finally a third dimension that seem to capture remaining variation. SI\ref{SI:dimensions} explains why we think three dimensions are the best description of the data. 

%We then interpreted the differences appearing between the sexes from the perspective of gender specialization. First, looking at the one dimensional description of sex specific age increases, we observe that boys have higher final knowledge than girls do. This difference appears during the juvenile period, between 7 and 12 years, right when division of labor begins to emerge. 

%But this one dimensional description of knowledge does not tell the whole story. Indeed, dividing knowledge into multiple dimensions can help understand how the age and sex patterns emerge. 

