\emph{Causal results:} where we consider plausible, but potentially biased, causal influences of activities, household family structure, and school attendance on knowledge. In each case, we control for unmeasured household-level variables, using random effects. This is because any correlation caused by some social characteristic associated to specific households can induce spurious correlations between the outcome variable, Knowledge, and the other variables that stay in the path of Family (see DAG in figure \ref{fig:DAG}). The posterior estimates for these random effects suggest that not much knowledge variation is due to differences between the families (see SI \ref{SI:other_factors}). However, the models are not designed to estimate the causal influence of unmeasured household variables, so these estimates cannot be interpreted causally, as is the norm with control variables \citep{Westreich2013TheCoefficients}.

The first variable we considered is the activities practiced by children (defined combining reports by parents and the children themselves, see SI \ref{SI:activities} for details), for which the effect on undifferentiated knowledge is substantial. Figure \ref{fig:activities_years} plots how much advantage, in terms of time, an individual can gain (positive effect) or lose (negative effect) from practicing a specific activity. All else being equal, a person who hunts birds can reach the same knowledge of a non-hunting 20 year old up to 10 years earlier. Similarly positive effects are given by collecting shellfish, fishing and by tending to the family's livestock. On the contrary, working in the fields can hinder knowledge acquisition by more than a decade, as can attending to household chores. Activities practiced account for majority of the measured difference between boys and girls, so that, once their effect is controlled for, the difference in knowledge between sexes seems to disappear (see figure S\ref{fig:zero_act}). 
Some portion of the measured association between activities and knowledge is plausibly causal, but note that there may be unmeasured common causes of both activity and knowledge, as well as some reverse causation, if knowledge is a necessary precondition for some activities. Therefore we suspect these activity effects are upper bound estimates.

We present the results of household family structure and school attendance in the Supplement \ref{SI:other_factors}. Co-residence of parents (figure S\ref{fig:parents_years}) appears to have an effect on individual's knowledge. Mothers seem to boost their children's knowledge, helping to reach earlier, on average, the same knowledge of a 20 years old with no parents. The presence of fathers, on the contrary, has different effect on his sons and daughters, improving the knowledge of the former, but impeding learning about the environment for the latter. Schooling seems to at least partially slow down learning for girls, but has no effect on boys (figure S\ref{fig:school_years}).  Birth order has no appreciable effect on knowledge (see figure S\ref{fig:birthorder_effects} and SI \ref{SI:other_factors} for more information).



