\section{Discussion}
%Knowledge increases non linearly
Our first result that humans learn during the whole pre-reproductive period complements previous work showing increases in knowledge during adolescence and adulthood  (e.g. \cite{Koster2016WisdomElders, Schniter2021Age-AppropriateChoyeros}). Additionally, we show that the rate of acquisition is not constant, and that there are age 'hot-spots' for learning. Knowledge acquisition appears in our data to be fastest during middle childhood, between 7 and 12 years, after which its speed decreases. 
More novel is our use of causal modelling to explore the role of activities in shaping sex differences in ecological knowledge. We find that higher ecological knowledge is associated with activities like foraging, hunting and fishing, consistent with the general view that practice is important to the acquisition of ecological information, and more distally that early life history is shaped by the need to learn. 

%Integrating the development of tissues, knowledge and behavior, 
Most hypotheses describing the importance of knowledge for life history evolution propose that childhood emerges in the \emph{Homo} lineage as a time to complete full growth of the brain during early childhood, after which the brain has to be filled with information during middle childhood \citep{Thompson2011MiddleOrigins}.
Our results are congruent with this view: after the brain reaches its full size, knowledge acquisition speeds up, maintaining a fast rate during the middle childhood years. Perhaps not incidentally, this period is marked by a slow down in somatic growth, which reduces the energetic requirements of children while they start to engage in productive activities and acquire the required knowledge.
Adult provisioning and protection are needed up to at least the beginning of adolescence, but the first attempts at performing most activities happen well before 12 years, and allow children to have a buffer zone in their life history in which to try out various tasks with the back up offered by parents and other caretakers \citep{Lew-Levy2018EvidenceBasin}.
During adolescence, learning is slower, although it keeps going until after sexual maturity, potentially providing opportunities for specialization. 

%gender specialization and dimensions
Differences in knowledge between the sexes appear by age 7 and becomes more prominent during adolescence. Although Pemban children of both sexes live in close contact with the natural and cultivated landscape, boys begin to  participate in more gender-specific activities in the forest and sea, such as hunting and fishing (see \cite{Lew-Levy2020Gender-TypedAdolescents} for further examples of cross-cultural variation in gender segregation during play). Shellfish collection is the main activity in the wild practiced preferentially by girls, but young boys often follow their sisters in these expeditions, and are therefore exposed to this kind of knowledge. Accordingly, the two sexes will typically differ to some extent in the amount of exposure to information about the environment, with boys having access to more girl-specific knowledge than the contrary. Indeed, while both sexes learn at the same rate knowledge that is shared, see dimension 1 in figure \ref{fig:dimensions}, boys have access to a whole area of information that is precluded to girls, which is represented in dimension 2 in the same figure. 
Our result could help explain why previous studies showed inconsistencies in the amount of knowledge differences found between the sexes \citep{Blacutt-Rivero2016LocalBolivia, Gallois2017LocalCulture, Schniter2021Age-AppropriateChoyeros, Setalaphruk2007ChildrensThailand, Cruz-garcia2018ChildrensInterface, Geng2016TraditionalProvince}. Indeed, the multidimensional nature of knowledge means that the survey design impacts the ability to measure knowledge evenly across dimensions, potentially overestimating the importance of one dimension above the others (e.g., a survey focusing on wild birds will show that males have much higher environmental knowledge, see SI \ref{SI:data_methods} for observations on how the types of data we collected vary in reflecting knowledge differences between sexes). %that methodological differences could account for this discrepancy, as can be deferentially investigated by certain survey tools rather than others.  

The importance of activities in promoting the differences between the sexes is confirmed by the causal analysis of their effect. Once we control for activities, we can see that the differences completely disappear (see figure S\ref{fig:zero_act}). %thus estimating knowledge of both sexes in a counterfactual condition in which nobody practices any activity,
Hunting, fishing and shellfish collection all have positive effect on knowledge, and they are practiced at different rates by boys and girls, so that knowledge differences between the sexes emerge through differential participation, rather than because of any presumed innate attitudes to environmental knowledge.

%In general, foraging in the natural environment is associated to higher ecological knowledge, whereas individuals who do not hunt nor gather are less knowledgeable, and most likely a large part of this association is causal. This is an important contribution to the idea that early life history is shaped by the need to learn, showing that practice and exposure to activities are important to acquire ecological information. 

%social environment
The differential participation in activities that involve the natural environment can also explain why residing with mothers appears to have a positive effect on knowledge for both girls and boys, but only the latter benefit from the presence of fathers. At least this would be the case if both sons and daughters learn from their mothers when collecting shellfish on the reef, but only sons learn to fish with their fathers. The fact that this is the only clear finding from our analysis of the effects of household composition on environmental knowledge may reflect the fact that children are immersed in a large and diverse social environment, which makes it difficult to investigate its effect on knowledge. As in so many contexts \citep{Boyette2017TeachingHunter-Gatherers, Lew-Levy2017HowSkills, Lew-Levy2019Inter-Congo}, kids are almost always surrounded by other adults, by older siblings or cousins, and by a varied set of peers and neighbours in play groups. Knowledge transmission is likely to happen through all of these ties, likely weakening any direct influences of household structure, particularly if children with few siblings are more likely to seek out neighbours and more distant relatives as playmates. Future investigations into the effects of the social environment on knowledge should probe friendship networks and household composition at a higher resolution. 

Our analysis of the effects of participation in formal education on ecological knowledge does not yield a clear answer on whether formal schooling impacts ecological knowledge, consistent with previous work  \citep{Reyes-Garcia2010SchoolingOther, Quinlan2016ChildrensVillage}. It is possible that the specific settings of the village where the data were collected (both forest and seashore are close-by) allow children to acquire enough experience of the natural environment irrespective of the amount of time they spend in formal education. But also, schooling might affect what children know about the environment, rather than only how much they know. It is even possible that information on other biomes learned at school substitutes for or even enhances locally relevant environmental knowledge. As such, no effect of schooling would be detected, as might be substituted by information on other biomes learned at school and result in no variation in total knowledge, as in our sample. 

%wrap up
In summary, our results support the idea that the pre-reproductive phase serves as a period for knowledge acquisition. First, we demonstrate that, among children and teenagers in Pemba, knowledge increases with age in a non linear fashion and that middle childhood is a hot-spot for learning. Second, we show how knowledge differences among sexes can be ascribed to different dimensions of knowledge, which reflect specialization. These differences are not innate, but seem to be a product of labor division, given the role played by activities in driving differentiation of knowledge. Third, we show the importance of practicing activities for knowledge acquisition and, fourth, we find some evidence that the social environment influences knowledge of children, but more specific analyses are needed in this sense.
All these results have significant implications for the hypotheses on the evolution of human early life history.
Knowledge cannot be acquired very early nor in a short time because of the crucial role that activities play, exposing individuals to relevant information. There are physical constraints to achieve adult rates of success in most foraging activities \citep{Bird2002ConstraintsGrowing, Bock2002LearningBotswana}, but children start trying them out much before they actually are physically apt and proficient \citep{Lew-Levy2021Cross-culturalSocieties}, and during this time they seem to be acquiring the necessary knowledge \citep{Lew-Levy2018EvidenceBasin}.
Faster learning, boosted for example by adapted innate behaviors, is probably not adaptive in humans because of the high behavioral flexibility we exhibit. Children have to learn in many different dimensions to complete different tasks, with differences between sexes and individual specialization. %And they are able to do so in a variety of contexts and environments, Pemba being only one of the possible ones. 

These insights on the evolution of childhood could be strengthened by applying comparable methods to samples from other populations, thereby providing a more nuanced understanding of the relationship between age and knowledge \cite{Deffner2021AGeneralizability}. With such data we can account for cultural variation, while at the same time produce comparable, non site-specific data to make adequate inferences on generalizable human learning patterns. For example, it might be interesting to examine whether the hot-spot age range identified in Pemba is a human universal, consistent with the âbrain-fillingâ hypothesis, or variable across sites, more consistent with the idea that learning schedules vary according to the ecological affordances offered by different environments and cultures.
 
Moreover, we advocate for the realization of longitudinal studies, tracking the variation of knowledge over time in the same child. This would allow us to draw individual learning curves, and thus estimate general trajectories of knowledge acquisition. Longitudinal studies would also allow us to better understand the direction of causation between participation in activities and knowledge about these activities, as well as the effect of social environments \citep{Redhead2021AResearch}.

Finally, we believe that understanding how and when ecological knowledge is acquired is an important goal in today's changing world. Local environmental knowledge is important to cope with climate change \citep{Berkes2002AdaptingCommunity}, and can boost the perceived value of plant foods, often considered weeds, which provide important ecosystem services \citep{Turner2011EdibleAgroecology}). In fact we know that agricultural societies rely on the natural (uncultivated) environment for multiple services: archaeological evidence proves that the transition to agriculture did not exclude foraged food from neolithic diets \citep{Ottoni2021TrackingCalculus}, modern populations fall back on wild foods in case of famine \citep{Walsh1995Eating:} and children are observed foraging in many different social settings \citep{Lee2009ChildrensShantytowns.}.
Hence we believe that our study on ecological knowledge of children in Pemba can add a relevant contribution to the literature on how societies can adapt to social and environmental transitions.

